name: Lampropeltis multifasciata (Bocourt, 1886)
occurrenceRemarks: Young adult female. This was Lampropeltis zonata "pulchra" (Latin meaning = "beauty") when I found it near Agua Dulce Creek 35 years ago. With extreme familiarity of how badly screwed-up the taxonomy of the genus Lampropeltis has become as of late, I hesitate to completely identify this beautiful Mountain King to species. Perhaps someone more familiar with, and accepting of the current revisions of the genus Lampropeltis will identify this Kingsnake to whatever "species" the ICZN (International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature) is calling it this month! name: Lampropeltis zonata (Lockington, 1835)
recordedBy: Adam G. Clause, Justin K. Clause, Marcy L. Kinsey, Gary R. Clause
occurrenceRemarks: SVL = 530mm, TL = 618mm, Mass = 26.8g.  Crawling across the paved two-lane highway, just after nightfall. Ambient air temperature 78° F. Surrounding habitat a narrow, interrupted strip of Quercus agrifolia woodland and riparian vegetation, nested in a matrix of grassy coastal sage scrub. A tributary of Lake Eleanor Creek, which eventually drains into Malibu Creek, crosses under the highway within 5 m of the snake’s location, but the creekbed near the culvert was only damp with no standing water visible. Poor body condition, skinny. Liver tissue in three tubes, “A,” “B,” and “C.” 3 Tissue tubes available.

occurrenceRemarks: On the crawl L. zonata #1. I was looking to my right, trying to figure out what was rustling in the forest, when I heard a noise to my right. I think I slightly startled this snake, who apparently was digesting a meal in a sunny spot just off the trail. I backed off, then crouched down to get these shots. The snake watched me for a bit, then after a little while slid off into the brush.

name: Lampropeltis zonata (Lockington, 1835)
occurrenceRemarks: On the crawl L. zonata #2. I was more than a little surprised to find this second kingsnake on the crawl towards the end of my hike. To be clear, none of the photos of this snake, or the previous, are staged. They are all exactly as I saw them. I followed this snake into the brush for a bit, reveling in my luck, then realized I had followed it into a mess of Poison Oak. Luckily, I'm pretty well immune to it. Still might have been worth it, though.

name: Lampropeltis zonata (Lockington, 1835)
occurrenceRemarks: My second encounter with an axanthic morph (lacking of any red/yellow pigmentation). This snake could easily be mistaken for the very similar L. getula, but when taking a closer look you will notice the black face/black nostril of this snake, something unique to L. zonata, whereas L. getula has a white face/white nostril. Spotted this snake not even 5ft off trail. Made for quite the easy handle, after only a few seconds of trying to slither away the snake got quite relaxed, laying still for minutes, allowing me to handle it for about 15 minutes in total before putting it back onto the granite boulder in which it was found. I’d say this was quite the healthy adult. About 2 1/2 to 3 ft in length, and seeming to have recently shed (the dorsal and ventral scales of the snake glistened dramatically in direct sunlight). So blessed to have come across yet another one of these more uncommon morphs for the species here in the Sierra.

name: Lampropeltis multifasciata (Bocourt, 1886)
occurrenceRemarks: Found by Sophie Cameron. Appeared to be drinking from the creek (photo 3 is as found). I was hopeful that my adventures in this canyon would be rewarded with one of these secretive snakes, but I never thought I would actually see one. I was out of my mind when I saw it and was more excited to find this guy than any other snake I have ever found. Was very bitey, and bit me and Sophie several times. At one point, it latched onto Sophie's shirt and held on, even chewing into the shirt like it was prey. One of my all time favorite wildlife encounters by far!!!

occurrenceRemarks: A friend sent me this photo of a beautiful Kingsnake for I D. Photo credit: A. Holberg. occurrenceRemarks: I came across what I believe may be a juvenile California Mountain Kingsnake - Lampropeltis Zonata while hiking down the Upper Yosemite Falls Trail around 10:07pm (22:07) on Friday, June 2, 2023. occurrenceRemarks: Unfortunately, this snake quickly slithered into a rock crack further than was possible to photograph. The right half of my sketch represents the part of the snake visible for a brief time before it moved, the left is the part visible after retreating into the rock. I understand that field sketches as “evidence of organism” is a contentious subject, however I do think that this species is distinctive enough to warrant posting as a verifiable observation. Any additional thoughts/input on this observation or on sketches as observations in general would be appreciated, as I’m not really sure of my opinion on whether they should be designated as casual myself.
